Fusarium tjaetaba is a soil-borne fungus that was first isolated from soil samples collected in the Tjae Taba region of Indonesia. The fungus is characterized by its production of sickle-shaped, multi-celled spores called macroconidia, which are a distinctive feature of many Fusarium species.

Limited information is available on the specific characteristics and ecological role of Fusarium tjaetaba, as it is a relatively newly described species. Further research is needed to understand its taxonomy, biology, and potential impacts on plant health or human health, if any.
